article.description: Vince Carter said a win over the Atlanta Hawks proves the Toronto Raptors have pride.
article.headline: Carter after win: 'We are playing for pride'
article.linkText: Carter says Raptors' win over Hawks was for pride
article.story:
TORONTO (AP) -- Vince Carter said a win over the Atlanta Hawks proves the Toronto Raptors have pride.
Carter

Carter made two free throws with 3.7 seconds left as Toronto ended its six-game losing streak with a 87-86 victory over the Hawks on Wednesday night. Carter finished with 27 points for the Raptors, who played their first home game after a 0-5 road trip. "You guys look at it as if we have no chance. We don't, but at the same time that's not a reason to quit,'' Carter said. "We are playing for a lot. We are playing for pride, we are playing for next year.'' Atlanta's Ira Newble fouled Carter as he threw up a desperation hook shot. The shot missed badly, but Carter made his free throws, giving Toronto a 87-86 lead. Shareef Abdur-Rahim couldn't get a shot off before the final buzzer sounded. "I thought Carter got bailed out on that last call,'' Atlanta coach Terry Stotts said. "It was a tough call to make to decide a game.'' Carter didn't expect to get the call. "I was so surprised I had to calm down to make sure I hit the free throws,'' Carter said. Jason Terry had 23 points and Abdur-Rahim had 22 for the Hawks, who have lost three straight. After Voshon Lenard's 3-pointer tied it at 81 with 2:37 left, Carter made a fadeaway jumper, giving Toronto its first lead since early in the third quarter. Terry followed with two free throws to tie it with 1:32 remaining, and Glenn Robinson's wide-open 3-pointer gave Atlanta a 86-83 lead with 1:00 left. Toronto's Alvin Williams followed with a jumper, cutting the lead to one. After Abdur-Rahim missed a 16-foot jumper, Toronto called a timeout to set up Carter's hook shot, on which he was double-teamed by Newble and Abdur-Rahim. Jerome Williams added 10 rebounds and eight points for the Raptors. Abdur-Rahim's layup capped a 9-0 run, giving Atlanta a 10-point lead -- its biggest lead of the game -- with 23 seconds left in the third quarter. Toronto responded with a 9-1 run to cut the lead to two with 9:27 left in the fourth. Embattled Toronto coach Lenny Wilkens replaced Morris Peterson in the starting lineup with Chris Jefferies. Jefferies went 2-for-7 for seven points, while Peterson went 1-for-8 from the field for just three points. "I was shocked,'' Jefferies said .

Game notes
Toronto's Antonio Davis did not return after leaving the game late in the third quarter with a bruised right knee. ... The Raptors went 12-for-20 from the free throw line. ... The Hawks shot 39.7 percent. ... Toronto outrebounded Atlanta 46-38.
